post.description:
Creates a new On Behalf Of (OBO) token. This token can be used to authenticate certain requests that must be performed by a third party such as Credit Card and Checking Account edit/update.

OBO tokens don't expire and can be safely exposed to the world as they don't authenticate sensitive operations.

post.summary: Creates a new user
post.description:
Creates a new user with the specified username and password. Username must be a valid email address. Passwords must implement the following rules:
  1. Must be at least 8 characters long (max 255)
  2. Must have at least one uppercase letter
  3. Must have at least one lowercase letter
  4. Must have at least one digit
  5. Must have at least one of the following special characters: #, Âª, ?, ^, @, -, _, $, &
  6. Must not contain the username
  7. Must be different from previous passwords

Additionally, passwords expire every 90 days.

post.summary: Authorize a transaction with SpeedChex
post.description:
Submit an authorization transaction to SpeedChex. Validates the transaction data packet for errors, performs basic routing and account number validation and optionally verifies the bank account using the Express Verify service.

Does not process the electronic check through the Federal Reserve, or verify or lock funds.

The account to authorize is identified by token.

post.summary: Capture a transaction with SpeedChex
post.description:
Schedules a previously authorized ECheck payment for
                      processing through the Federal Reserve at the next End-of-Day Batch
                      Settlement date/time.

post.summary: Process a payment transaction with SpeedChex
post.description:
Processes payments from or payments to a bank account.
                      Performs an ECheck.Authorize and ECheck.Capture in a single command.
                      Payment is only processed to the Federal Reserve if it passes the
                      authorization process.

put.description: Modifies a transaction if it has not yet been sent to the Federal Reserve for processing.

post.summary: Refund a transaction with SpeedChex
post.description:
Reverses a previous debit that has settled (Cleared) and
                      refunds the same amount (or less if specified) to the same bank
                      account as the original referenced debit. Refunds are automatically
                      captured for settlement.

post.summary: Void a transaction with SpeedChex
post.description: Cancels (stops) a transaction from processing to the Federal Reserve.

post.summary: Hold a transaction with SpeedChex
post.description:
Places a scheduled transaction on âMerchant Holdâ if it
                      has not yet been sent to the Federal Reserve for processing. This is a
                      delay in processing that a merchant may impose on a transaction until
                      they are ready to remove the hold.

post.summary: Remove hold a transaction with SpeedChex
post.description:
Removes the âMerchant Holdâ status on a transaction and
                      reschedules the transaction for processing on the date specified in
                      the command.

post.summary: Verify bank account information with SpeedChex
post.description:
Performs basic algorithm verification on a routing
                      number and account number and optionally verifies the bank account
                      using the Express Verify service.

post.summary: Validate credit cards in bulk for import
post.description:
Upload a file containing credit card information to be imported. The file is a Comma Separated Value (CSV) file containing one credit card per row.

The layout for the file is:

cardholder name,expiration date (MMYYYY),card number,address,city,2 letter state code,zipcode,3 letter country code

Each field separated by a comma. For example, a valid row:

John doe,012017,4111111111111111,123 Oak Lane,Schenectady,NY,12345,USA

Each row is validated only. No credit card information is modified in any way.

post.summary: Import a previously validated checking account file
Validate checking accounts in bulk for import
post.description:
Upload a file containing checking account information to be imported. The file is a Comma Separated Value (CSV) file containing one checking account per row.

The layout for the file is:

account number,routing number,account type(checking or savings),eft branch number (EFT only),eft institution number (EFT only),bank name,accountholder name,address,city,2 letter state code,zipcode,3 letter country code

Each field separated by a comma. Optional fields are skipped by leaving the option empty. For example, a valid US account row:

123456789,987654321,checking,,,,John doe,123 Oak Lane,Schenectady,NY,12345,USA

Spaces are significant, so if a field is set as 

someval, ,someother
the field in the middle would be set to a single space value.

Each row is validated only. No checking account information is modified in any way.

post.summary: Validate transactions for bulk updates to transactions
post.description:
Upload a file containing transactions status updates. The file is a Comma Separated Value (CSV) file containing the details of one transaction per row.

The layout for the file is:

transaction_id,new_status,response_code,comments

Each field separated by a comma. For example, a valid row:

123, R05

Response codes are expected to be standard NACHA or CPA response code. This code will mark the transaction as successfully completed.
